ce:section.ce:para:
The quantitative detection of Fu was performed under the optimal detection conditions by recording the FL emission spectra and intensity of the prepared-CDs at 435 nm with the addition of different amount of Fu, which the concentrations were 0, 0.5, 1, 5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90 and 100 μM, respectively. As shown in Fig. 8
                        A, with increasing the concentrations of Fu from 0 to 100 μM, the FL intensity of CDs solution containing Fu decreased at the FL emission wavelength of 435 nm. After the Fu concentration reached 100 μM, the degree of FL quenching was 83.2%, which suggested that Fu could significantly quenched the FL intensity of CDs. We made a graph with the Fu concentration as the abscissa and the ln(F0/F) value as the ordinate. Obviously, a linear curve was obtained between the ln(F0/F) and the Fu concentrations changing from 0.5 to 100 μM. The corresponding linear fitting equation of the fluorescence detection system was ln(F0/F) = 0.018[Fu]-0.049 (R2 = 0.996), and the detection limit (LOD) reached 0.096 μM (S/N = 3). Compared to other analytical methods, this fluorescence method proposed wider linear detection ranges or lower detection limit (Table 2
                        ). In short, this proposed fluorescence detection probe revealed extensive advantages of easy operation, low cost, and facile “turn off” procedure, which was an important foundation for the determination of Fu in real samples.
